Problem Statement

Business Context

Understanding customer personality and behavior is pivotal for businesses to enhance customer satisfaction and increase revenue. Segmentation based on a customer's personality, demographics, and purchasing behavior allows companies to create tailored marketing campaigns, improve customer retention, and optimize product offerings.

A leading retail company with a rapidly growing customer base seeks to gain deeper insights into their customers' profiles. The company recognizes that understanding customer personalities, lifestyles, and purchasing habits can unlock significant opportunities for personalizing marketing strategies and creating loyalty programs. These insights can help address critical business challenges, such as improving the effectiveness of marketing campaigns, identifying high-value customer groups, and fostering long-term relationships with customers.

With the competition intensifying in the retail space, moving away from generic strategies to more targeted and personalized approaches is essential for sustaining a competitive edge.

Objective

In an effort to optimize marketing efficiency and enhance customer experience, the company has embarked on a mission to identify distinct customer segments. By understanding the characteristics, preferences, and behaviors of each group, the company aims to:

  1. Develop personalized marketing campaigns to increase conversion rates.
  2. Create effective retention strategies for high-value customers.
  3. Optimize resource allocation, such as inventory management, pricing strategies, and store layouts.

As a data scientist tasked with this project, your responsibility is to analyze the given customer data, apply machine learning techniques to segment the customer base, and provide actionable insights into the characteristics of each segment.

Data Dictionary

The dataset includes historical data on customer demographics, personality traits, and purchasing behaviors. Key attributes are:

  1. Customer Information

    • ID: Unique identifier for each customer.
    • Year_Birth: Customer's year of birth.
    • Education: Education level of the customer.
    • Marital_Status: Marital status of the customer.
    • Income: Yearly household income (in dollars).
    • Kidhome: Number of children in the household.
    • Teenhome: Number of teenagers in the household.
    • Dt_Customer: Date when the customer enrolled with the company.
    • Recency: Number of days since the customers last purchase.
    • Complain: Whether the customer complained in the last 2 years (1 for yes, 0 for no).

  2. Spending Information (Last 2 Years)

    • MntWines: Amount spent on wine.
    • MntFruits: Amount spent on fruits.
    • MntMeatProducts: Amount spent on meat.
    • MntFishProducts: Amount spent on fish.
    • MntSweetProducts: Amount spent on sweets.
    • MntGoldProds: Amount spent on gold products.

  3. Purchase and Campaign Interaction

    • NumDealsPurchases: Number of purchases made using a discount.
    • AcceptedCmp1: Response to the 1st campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp2: Response to the 2nd campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp3: Response to the 3rd campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp4: Response to the 4th campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp5: Response to the 5th campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • Response: Response to the last campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).

  4. Shopping Behavior

    • NumWebPurchases: Number of purchases made through the companys website.
    • NumCatalogPurchases: Number of purchases made using catalogs.
    • NumStorePurchases: Number of purchases made directly in stores.
    • NumWebVisitsMonth: Number of visits to the companys website in the last month.

In[15]:
#Creating elbow plot
# step 1 - creaing an empty dictionary to store the within-cluster sum of squares
WCSS = {}

# step 2 - iterate for a range of K clusters (from 1-9) for the scaled data. kmeans.inertia_ stores the values of the WCSS for each cluster. I added random_state so that iteration will start at the same point each time it is run.
for k in range(1, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, max_iter=1000, random_state=1)
    kmeans.fit(data_scaled)
    WCSS[k] = kmeans.inertia_

# step 3 - here we plot the within cluster sum of squares versus cluster size. To find optimal clusters you find the point at which there is the sharpest curve (i.e. the elbow)
plt.figure()
plt.plot(list(WCSS.keys()), list(WCSS.values()), 'bx-')
plt.xlabel("Number of clusters")
plt.ylabel("WCSS")
plt.show()
Observations:

Using the elbow method above, it appears that the optimal number of clusters is 2 or 3. Since the drop off is steeper at 2 clusters, I would begin with that number.

Question 8 : finalize appropriate number of clusters by checking the silhoutte score as well. Is the answer different from the elbow plot?

In[16]:
#Empty dictionary to store the Silhouette score for each value of k
sc = {}

# iterate for a range of K clusters from 2-9 (cannot run this with 1 cluster) and fit the scaled data. Store the Silhouette score for that k
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1).fit(data_scaled)
    labels = kmeans.predict(data_scaled)
    sc[k] = silhouette_score(data_scaled, labels)

#Elbow plot of silhouette score versus number of clusters
plt.figure()
plt.plot(list(sc.keys()), list(sc.values()), 'bx-')
plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")
plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")
plt.show()
Observations:

Using the silhouette method, it appears that the optimal number of clusters is 3, however 5 is an option as well. Since the elbow method indicated either 2 or 3 cluster, I will chose 3 for the appropriate number of clusters as this incorporates both methods.

There are three groups labeled 0, 1, 2 with 635, 1043, and 562 observations in each, respectively. Group 2 is your higher income cluster and group 1 is your lower income cluster. You can see that the higher income cluster tends to spend more in all categories (sweets, fish, fruit, meat and wine), however there appears to be more outliers in group 0 and 1.

Interestingly, cluster 1 has the highest number of web visits per month, but have the lowest number of web purchases among the clusters. Potentially, this could indicate that they are browsing and comparing prices/deals to other stores. This group also has the lowest number of in store purchase, which in conjunction to the web browsing data may indicate that this group is purchasing elsewhere because our prices are too high for them.

Cluster 2 had the highest in store and catalog purchases. These shoppers may be more loyal customers because they are receiving a catalog from our store and making more purchases in store. Because of this they may also be less price sensitive (i.e. willing to purchase an item whether it is full price or on sale). This makes sense with cluster 0, as they have higher incomes they are most likely less price sensitive anyway.

Lastly, it appears that cluster 1 has more children at home and with the lower income group, and this makes sense as this cluster also has the lowest median age.

Business Recommedations

Question 12: Based on the cluster insights, what business recommendations can be provided?

Based on the clusters and objectives of the project, I would make the following recommendations:

Objective 1: Develop personalized marketing campaigns to increase conversion rates

Recommendation 1: Cluster 1 (the lower income group) tends to have the highest web visits but lowest web purchases. As mentioned previously, this may indicate that the group is shopping for the best/lowest deals, then finding it elsewhere and not converting to a sale for our company. This may be a group to target marketing in that you can advertize to them with a discount for online purchasing, or even advertize online for in-store sales to motivate them to come into the store to purchase items.

Objective 2: Create effective retention strategies for high-value customers

Recommendation 2: Cluster 2 contains the high-value customers, meaning they tend to spend the most on products across the board and are most loyal to the company. Even though they are high loyalty customers, you want to ensure that you are retaining these customers for the long-term. To do this, I would recommend implementing a loyalty or rewards program offering them discounts or money back after spending a certain dollar amount. Another option could be offering birthday rewards for these customers giving them money off during their birthday month or even targetting their product preferences with free or discounted bottle of wine or sweet item (slice of cake) for their birthday. Additionally you could implement exclusive benefits for being a loyalty member including sales that are specifically targetting this group or early access to an upcoming sale.

Recommendation 3: Cluster 0 has the highest web purchases of all three clusters. Interestingly, the number of web purchases is higher than number of web visits. I would think that in order to purchase, you have to visit the website, so I would expect visits to be higher than purchases. However, potentially customers make a purchase, then return to the site to purchase additional items they forgot to order, or maybe they purchase multiple times in a week/month and those are counted only as one web visit. I would want to clarify this. Whatever the reason, this cluster seems more consistent with web purchases/visits, so targeting them for online promotions or rewards might be beneficial to retain them as the online customer base.

Objective 3: Optimize resource allocation, such as inventory management, pricing strategies, and store layouts

Recommendation 4: Clusters 0 and 2 tend to spend the most on wine and meat. These groups also have higher number of in-store purchases. When considering store layout, it may make sense to place wine near the meats to encourage customers to purchase the two items together.

Recommendation 5: As discussed previously, the total amount spent on items from highest to lowest was for wine, meat, fish, and lastly fruit/sweets are fairly similar. Knowing this can help the company estimate what type and how much inventory to stock in our store or warehouses. However, this is somewhat misleading because fruits and sweets are typically cheaper to buy compared to meat, fish, and wine, so customers may be spending a higher dollar amount on higher priced items, they may be purchasing larger volume of the lower priced items. For example, a customer purchases a 30 dollar bottle of wine but may need to purchase 6 items in the sweets category to amount to 30 dollars. Even so, this does give us a general idea of how to stock products.

Recommendation 6: Cluster 1 appears to be our least loyal customer group, but may have the most potential for increased sales. I might recommend offering them discounts for the first 90 days of their membership to increase likelihood of them purchasing from our store, with the hope that they will enjoy our product offerings and continue converting to sales once the discount period is over.
